{{Dome architecture}}
Cultures from [[Prehistory|pre-history]] to modern times constructed [[dome]]d dwellings using local materials. Although it is not known when or where the first dome was created, sporadic examples of early domed structures have been discovered. Brick domes from the [[ancient Near East]] and [[Corbel arch|corbelled]] stone domes have been found from the Middle East to Western Europe. These may indicate a common source or multiple independent traditions. A variety of materials have been used, including wood, mudbrick, or fabric. Indigenous peoples around the world produce similar structures today.
== Early and indigenous domes == [[File:Apache Wickiup, Edward Curtis, 1903.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Photo of an Apache wigwam, by Edward S. Curtis, 1903.]] The earliest domes were likely domed huts made from saplings, reeds, or timbers and covered with [[Thatching|thatch]], [[Sod|turf]], or skins. Materials may have transitioned to [[rammed earth]], [[mud-brick]], or more durable stone as a result of local conditions.{{sfn|Mainstone|2001|p=116}} The earliest discovered remains of domed constructions may be four small dwellings made of [[Mammoth]] tusks and bones. The first was found by a farmer in [[Mezhirich]], Ukraine, in 1965 while he was digging in his cellar and archaeologists unearthed three more.{{sfn|Hitchcock}} They date from 19,280 - 11,700 BC.{{sfn|Palmer|Pettitt|Bahn|2005|p=24}}
More recently, semi-subterranean dwellings of the [[Thule people]], ancestors of the [[Inuit]] who were established in the [[Northern Canada|Canadian Arctic]] by 1300 AD, were made of whalebone frames lashed together with [[Hide (skin)|hide]] straps in a [[Parabola|parabolic]] dome shape covered with hides and blocks of [[sod]] and snow.{{sfn|Levy|Dawson|2009|p=2298-9, 2301-2}} The [[igloo]], a shelter built from blocks of ice in a spiral, was used by the Inuit people. The [[wigwam]] was made by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] and covered with hides or bark.{{sfn|Hosey|2012|p=138-139}}
In developing countries, domes are often less expensive alternatives to flat or sloped-roofed construction because they use less material to enclose a given volume and provide a lower rate of heat transfer due to the reduced surface area. Domes made with [[loam]] are found in Europe, Asia, and Africa, almost always using mud-bricks or [[adobe]]s. A way of building them without centering called the Persian dome technique has been used for centuries in [[Afghanistan]].{{sfn|Minke|2012|p=119, 127}} The examples of [[Beehive house|beehive domes]] at [[Harran]], Turkey, have been dated to the 19th century AD, and are similar to the [[trullo]]s of Italy.{{sfn|Sami|Özdemir|2011|p=153}} The [[Efé people]] of central Africa construct similar [[Hut (dwelling)|structures]], using leaves as shingles.{{sfn|Wilkie|Morelli|2000}} The [[Himba people]] of [[Namibia]] construct "desert igloos" of [[wattle and daub]] for use as temporary shelters at seasonal cattle camps, and as permanent homes by the poor.{{sfn|Crandall|2000|p=34-35}} Extraordinarily thin [[Musgum mud huts|domes of sun-baked clay]] 20 feet in diameter, 30 feet high, and nearly parabolic in curve, are known from [[Cameroon]].{{sfn|Creswell|1915a|p=155}}
The historical development from structures like these to more sophisticated domes is not well documented. That the dome was known to early [[Mesopotamia]] may explain the existence of domes in both [[China]] and [[Western World|the West]] in the first millennium BC.{{sfn|Hill|1996|p=69}} Another explanation, however, is that the use of the dome shape in construction did not have a single point of origin and was common in virtually all cultures long before domes were constructed with enduring materials.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=6}}
== Ancient Near East == [[File:Vault fig 01.gif|thumb|right|200px|Drawing of an Assyrian bas-relief from Nimrud.]] Small domes in corbelled stone or brick over round-plan houses go back to the [[Neolithic|Neolithic period]] in the [[ancient Near East]], and served as dwellings for poorer people throughout the [[Prehistory|prehistoric period]], but domes did not play an important role in monumental architecture.{{sfn|Leick|2003|p=64}} The discoveries of [[Cylinder seal|seal]] impressions in the ancient site of [[Chogha Mish]] (c. 6800 to 3000 BC), located in the [[Susiana]] plains of [[Iran]], show the extensive use of dome structures in mud-brick and [[adobe]] buildings, likely granaries.{{sfn|Delougaz|Kantor|1996|p=131-132, 143}} Other examples of mud-brick buildings that also seemed to employ the "true" dome technique have been excavated at [[Tell Arpachiyah]], a Mesopotamian site of the [[Tell Halaf|Halaf]] (c. 6100 to 5400 BC) and [[Ubaid period|Ubaid]] (ca. 5300 to 4000 BC) cultures.{{sfn|Leick|2003|p=202}} Excavations at [[Tell al-Rimah]] have revealed pitched-brick domical vaults from about 2000 BC.{{sfn|Kawami|1982|p=63}}
At the [[Sumer]]ian Royal Cemetery of [[Ur]], a "complete rubble dome built over a timber centring" was found among the chambers of the tombs for [[Meskalamdug]] and [[Puabi]], dating to around 2500 BC.{{sfn|Chant|Goodman|1999|p=23}} Set in mud mortar, it was a "true dome with pendentives rounding off the angles of the square chamber." Other small domes can be inferred from the remaining ground plans, such as one in the courtyard of [[Ur-Nammu]]'s ziggurat, and in later shrines and temples of the 14th century BC.{{sfn|Kubba|1987|p=114}} Some monumental Mesopotamian buildings of the [[Kassites|Kassite]] period are thought to have had brick domes, but the issue is unsettled due to insufficient evidence in what has survived of these structures.{{sfn|Leick|2003|p=64}}
A [[Neo-Assyrian Empire|Neo-Assyrian]] [[Relief|bas-relief]] from [[Nineveh|Kuyunjik]] depicts domed buildings, although remains of such a structure in that ancient city have yet to be identified, perhaps due to the impermanent nature of sun-dried [[mudbrick]] construction.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=62}}{{sfn|Spiers|1911|p=957}} However, because the relief depicts the Assyrian overland transport of a carved stone statue, the background buildings most likely refer to a foreign village, such as those at the foothills of the [[Mount Lebanon|Lebanese mountains]]. The relief dates to the 8th century BC, while the use of domical structures in the [[Syria]]n region may go back as far as the fourth millennium BC.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=61-62}} Likewise, domed houses at [[Shulaveri-Shomu culture|Shulaveri]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] and [[Khirokitia]], Cyprus, date back to around 6000 BC.{{sfn|Sami|Özdemir|2011|p=153}}
== Ancient Middle East and Mediterranean == [[File:Schatzhaus des Atreus, Querschnitt.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Drawing of the so-called [[Treasury of Atreus]] in Mycenae, Greece.]] Ancient stone corbelled domes have been found from the Middle East to Western Europe. Corbelled beehive domes were used as granaries in [[Ancient Egypt]] from the [[First dynasty of Egypt|first dynasty]], in [[mastaba]] tombs of the [[Old Kingdom]], as pressure-relieving devices in private brick pyramids of the [[New Kingdom]], and as kilns and cellars. They have been found in brick and in stone.{{sfn|Arnold|2003}} The mastaba tombs of [[Seneb]] and of Neferi are examples.{{sfn|Leick|2003|p=64}} A model of a [[Tenth Dynasty of Egypt|10th dynasty]] house has also been found in [[Rifeh]] showing the tops of three domes just emerging through the terraced roof.{{sfn|Creswell|1915a|p=147}}
In an area straddling the borders between [[Oman]], [[UAE]], and [[Bahrain]], stone [[beehive tomb]]s built above ground called "Hafit graves", or "Mezyat graves", date to the [[Hafit period]] between 3200 and 2700 BC.{{sfn|National|2010}}{{sfn|ADACH|2012}} Similar above-ground tombs made of corbelled stone domes have been found in the [[Cataracts of the Nile|fourth cataract region]] of [[Nubia]] with dates beginning in the second millennium BC.{{sfn|Paner|Borcowski|2007|p=2, 9}} The "Nubian dome" technique of using a movable guide to lay courses of a spherical dome dates back thousands of years in [[Upper Egypt]].{{sfn|Minke|2012|p=128}}
Examples on the Mediterranean island of [[Sardinia]] have been dated to 2500 BC.{{sfn|McNeil|2002|p=883}}
[[Minoan civilization|Minoan]] free-standing tombs about 4 to 13 meters in diameter are partially preserved on the [[Messara Plain]] of Crete. Only the lowest 3 or 4 meters remain standing of structures that may have risen up to 12 meters, but they are generally agreed to have been domed and provide a developmental link between Neolithic round houses and the circular tombs of the [[Bronze Age]]. They are dated after the round houses of [[Prehistoric Cyprus#Chalcolithic|Chalcolithic western Cyprus]] and before the Mycenaean [[Beehive tomb|"tholoi"]].{{sfn|Wright|2009|p=13}}
The so-called "[[Treasury of Atreus]]", a large [[Mycenaean chamber tomb|Mycenaean tomb]] covered with a mound of earth, dates to around 1330 BC.{{sfn|McNeil|2002|p=883}} It is about 15 meters in diameter and one of several tholos tombs with corbelled domes.{{sfn|Hourihane|2012|p=303}} Others include the "[[Tomb of Clytemnestra|Treasury of Clytemnestra]]" and the "Treasury of Minyas". Such underground tombs ("treasury" was a term used by [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] for the grave of a hero) flourished in Mycenaean Greece between 1500 BC and 1300 BC, increasing in diameter from about 8 meters to about 14 meters in that time.{{sfn|Wright|2009|p=179}} Smaller scale examples from this time can also be found in other parts of southern and western Europe.{{sfn|Mainstone|2001|p=116}} Corbelled beehive tombs over square chambers appear in [[Thrace]], the [[Crimea]], and in [[Etruria]] in the first millennium BC. Corbelling in the corners created pendentives.{{sfn|Wright|2009|p=188}}
Wooden domes were evidently used in Etruria on the Italian peninsula from [[Archaic Greece|archaic times]]. Reproductions were preserved as rock-cut Etruscan tombs produced until the Roman [[Roman Empire|Imperial period]], and paintings at [[Pompeii]] show examples of them in the [[Pompeian Styles#Third Style|third style]] and later.{{sfn|Lehmann|1945|p=248-249}} Built between the eighth century and the first century BC, particularly around [[Tarquinia]] and [[Cerveteri]], thousands of examples of Etruscan domed tombs have been identified.{{sfn|Melaragno|1991|p=9}} The Etruscan "Tomb of the Diavolino" at [[Vetulonia]] is an example.{{sfn|Mainstone|2001|p=117}}
Wooden domes may also have been used in [[ancient Greece]], over buildings such as the [[Epidaurus|Tholos of Epidaurus]], which is typically depicted with a shallow conical roof.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=11}} Evidence for such wooden domes over round buildings in ancient Greece, if they existed, has not survived and the issue is much debated.{{sfn|Lehmann|1945|p=248}} The [[heroon]] at [[Stymfalia|Stymphalos]] has been dated to the late [[Classical Greece|Classical]] or early [[Hellenistic period]] and has a round room preceded by a long rectilinear porch. Its layout might have been copied from Mycenaean tholos tombs and, still in use in the Roman period, it has also been suggested as an inspiration or precedent for the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] in Rome.{{sfn|Williams|2005|p=404}}{{sfn|Jones|2003|p=180}}
== Hellenistic and pre-Roman domes == Although they had palaces of brick and stone, the kings of [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid Persia]] held audiences and festivals in domical tents derived from the nomadic traditions of central Asia. They were likely similar to the [[Yurt|later tents]] of the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol Khans]]. Called "Heavens", the tents emphasized the cosmic significance of the divine ruler. They were adopted by [[Alexander the Great]] after his conquest of the empire, and the domed [[baldachin]] of Roman and Byzantine practice was presumably inspired by this association.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=81-82}}
Simple domical mausoleums existed in the [[Hellenistic period]].{{sfn|Grabar|1963|p=194}} The possible use of domed ceilings in the architecture of [[Ptolemaic Kingdom|Ptolemaic Egypt]] is suggested by rock-cut tombs in [[Alexandria]] and by a poem from a third century BC [[papyrus]] that references a fountain [[Niche (architecture)|niche]] covered with a semi-dome.{{sfn|Winter|2006|p=169}}
The earliest physical evidence of a Hellenistic dome is at the [[Morgantina#North Baths|North Baths of Morgantina]] in [[Sicily]], dated to the mid third century BC. The dome measured 5.75 metres in diameter over the circular hot room of the baths. It was made of [[terracotta]] tubes partially inserted into each other and arranged in parallel arches that were then completely covered with mortar. Iron pins were used to connect some of the tubes horizontally. It is also the earliest known example of this technique of tubular vault construction. A Hellenistic bathing complex in nearby [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]] may also have used domes like these to cover its circular rooms. The domes are contemporaneous with [[Archimedes]], and the technique of their construction may be related to his method of analyzing spheres as a series of parallel truncated cone segments. The ship ''[[Syracusia]]'', built for [[Hiero II of Syracuse]] and construction of which was overseen by Archimedes, included a domed library.{{sfn|Lucore|2009|p=43-53}}
In the city of [[Pergamon]], there are remains of stone [[Apse|apsidal]] semi-domes from the second century BC.{{sfn|Dodge|1984|p=285}} The earliest evidence for [[Ashlar|dressed stone]] domes with [[voussoir]]s comes from the first century BC in the region of Palestine, Syria, and southern Anatolia, the "heartland of Oriental Hellenism".{{sfn|Wright|2009|p=188}} A stone pendentive dome is known from a first century BC bath in [[Petra]].{{sfn|Bardill|2008|p=340}}
The [[Scythians]] built domed tombs, as did some [[Germanic peoples|Germanic]] tribes in a [[paraboloid]] shape.{{sfn|Melaragno|1991|p=9}} In the [[Saarland|Saar basin]] of the [[Germania|Germanic north of Europe]], the domical shape was used in wooden construction over houses, tombs, temples, and city towers, and was translated into masonry construction only after the beginning of Roman rule.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=11}}
The remains of a large domed circular hall measuring 17 meters in diameter in the [[Parthian Empire|Parthian]] capital city of [[Nisa, Turkmenistan|Nyssa]] has been dated to perhaps the first century AD. It "shows the existence of a monumental domical tradition in Central Asia that had hitherto been unknown and which seems to have preceded Roman Imperial monuments or at least to have grown independently from them."{{sfn|Grabar|1963|p=192}} It likely had a wooden dome.{{sfn|Ashkan|Ahmad|2009|p=99}} The Sun Temple at [[Hatra]] appears to indicate a transition from columned halls with [[trabeated]] roofing to vaulted and domed construction in the first century AD, at least in Mesopotamia. The domed sanctuary hall of the temple was preceded by a barrel vaulted [[iwan]], a combination that would be used by the subsequent Persian [[Sasanian Empire]].{{sfn|Stronach|1976|p=623}} An account of a Parthian domed palace hall from around 100 AD in the city of Babylon can be found in the ''[[Life of Apollonius of Tyana]]'' by [[Philostratus]]. The hall was used by the king for passing judgments and was decorated with a mosaic of blue stone to resemble the sky, with images of gods in gold.{{sfn|Lehmann|1945|p=250-251}} A bulbous Parthian dome can be seen in the relief sculpture of the [[Arch of Septimius Severus]] in Rome, its shape apparently due to the use of a light tent-like framework.{{sfn|Smith|1950|p=82}}
