{{About|the symphony by [[Joseph Haydn]]|the symphony by [[Michael Haydn]]|Symphony No. 36 (Michael Haydn)}}
[[Joseph Haydn]] wrote his '''Symphony No. 36''' in [[E-flat major|E{{music|b}} major]], Hoboken 1/36, some time in the first half of the 1760s, around the same time as his [[Symphony No. 33 (Haydn)|Symphony No. 33]], for Prince [[Nikolaus Esterházy]]. Scored for 2 [[oboe]]s, [[bassoon]], 2 [[Natural horn|horn]]s, [[String section|strings]] and [[Basso continuo|continuo]], the slow movement features solos for [[violin]] and [[cello]].<ref>H. C. Robbins Landon, ''The Symphonies of Joseph Haydn''. London: Universal Edition & Rockliff (1955): 669. "2 ob., 2 cor., vln. solo (in II), vcl. solo (in II), str. [fag., cemb.]."</ref> It is in four movements:

#[[Tempo#Italian tempo markings|Vivace]], {{music|time|3|4}}
#[[Tempo#Italian tempo markings|Adagio]] in [[B-flat major|B{{music|flat}} major]], {{music|time|2|2}}
#[[Menuet]] – [[trio (music)|Trio]] (Trio in [[B-flat major|B{{music|flat}} major]]), {{music|time|3|4}}
#[[Tempo#Italian tempo markings|Allegro]], {{music|time|2|4}}

